-given nation builder, cut in the model of George Washington. But in this campaign, the massacre of thousands of Jews perceived as Polish intermediaries was the collateral damage, and in order to secure the tentative independence, Khmelnytsky signed a treaty with Moscow, ultimately ceding the territory to the Russian tsar. So, was he a liberator or a villain? This volume examines drastically different narratives, from Ukrainian, Jewish, Russian, and Polish literature, that have sought to animate, deify, and vilify the seventeenth-century Cossack. Khmelnytsky's legacy, either as nation builder or as antagonist, has inhibited inter-ethnic and political rapprochement at key moments throughout history and, as we see in recent conflicts, continues to affect Ukrainian, Jewish, Polish, and Russian national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCossack-Polish War, 1648-1657xLiterature and the war. 0aCossacks in literature. 4a1648 uprising. 4aBohdan Khmelnytsky. 4aCossacks. 4aJewish literary history. 4aPolish-Lithuanian Commonwealth. 4aRussian-Ukrainian cultural relations. 4aUkrainian history. 4aUkrainian-Jewish relations. 4anationalism and charisma. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aGlaser, Amelia M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804794961zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804794961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804794961.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles